english:
  title: Colophon on the Poetry Collection Presented to Hong the Licentiates by Master Ugok and Other Worthies
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In Bucye of Seonsan, the Hong family dwelt, and their mother was known for her filial devotion. When Hong returned from his studies and service in the capital, Master Jeong of Ugok composed parting verses that recounted the glory of the Munheon lineage—father and son, brothers all—who served as examiners of the realm. It is said his mother was the tenth-generation descendant of the Choi clan. At that time, the great luminaries of the literati—Master Ikjae, Master Geupam Min, Master Choeunn Lee, Yuansang of Chilwon, Master Yu of Danyang, Do-sa Yun of Yikyang, Jeongshan Jeong of Maegye, Minister Sim of Iljin, and Scholar-official Huh of Yangcheon—all composed verses matching his rhyme. And Pyeongzhang Hwang of Hoesan, who wandered between Confucianism and Taoism and delighted in poetic exchange, likewise admired Hong's virtue and offered his composition. Twenty-six years have now passed.

    Hong's name is Minseek, his courtesy name Haogo, bestowed by Master Ikjae. He rose together with Yeom Dongjung, this year's Chief Examiner, both achieving licentiates' rank in the year of Gyesa. Thus when the examinations were held, all said, 'Haogo has found his patron in the Chief Examiner. Dongjung will surely elevate this elder through his gate and claim his fellow-licerentiate as his disciple.' Yet Haogo's own heart could not help but harbor some hope that the examiner might take pity and accept him. And yet—speaking of human will is to speak of fairness; speaking of Heaven is to speak of fate. That after twenty-six years of old bonds he was not included in a single morning's selection—can we call it anything but Heaven's decree? Can we call it anything but fairness?

    When a scholar enters the world, he reads in his youth and does not cease in his age. For what purpose? It is to understand the origin of nature and to penetrate the root of gain and loss, so that nowhere does he fail to attain self-knowledge. Observing Haogo's words and countenance, truly he is one whose inner being flows freely—truly one who understands fate. Since I rose through examination, I have twice served as examiner, and many of my same-year graduates have suffered rejection and departed. When facing the examination papers, I fix my mind and direct my gaze steadily, listening solely to Heaven's justice. How could I spare a moment's thought for my year-mates and old friends? If I cannot spare thought for them, how could I spare thought for whether they come from humble or distinguished families? That Haogo attains his freedom through self-knowledge is as it should be. Dongjung's heart is my heart. That Haogo attains his freedom through self-knowledge is as it should be. And moreover, at but forty-four years of age, what he may yet accomplish cannot be measured. Haogo has said, 'The world tells of Liang Ning, who at eighty-two finally passed the examination and even came to preside over the selections. How dare I set limits upon myself?' His words are noble, and I admire him all the more. Though Dongjung did not request it of me, I was prepared to support him. How much more so when he writes asking that I speak for Haogo! Therefore I record this, that it may serve as a model for future examiners in selecting their candidates.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Bucye (缶溪): An alternate name for Bugyeong, located in Seonsan (present-day Gimhae), known as a center of Confucian learning.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Munheon (文憲): Refers to Choi Chung, an important historical figure whose descendants held prominent positions as examiners.'
  - key: ''
    value: The listed masters and officials represent the intellectual elite of the era, many known for their poetic talents and Confucian scholarship.
  - key: ''
    value: 'Liang Ning: A historical figure known for achieving examination success despite his advanced age, serving as a model of perseverance.'
